He attended the New Orleans Center for Creative Arts (NOCCA), a public performing and visual arts high school, graduating in 2006.
In 2013, the band released Nameless Neighbors on Sunnyside Records.
The album was included in The Times-Picayune's "2013 list of best jazz records".
In 2015, Sunnyside Records released the trio's second album, entitled You Are a Creature, which like their debut was produced by Hersch.
In February 2015, the album was included in DownBeat's "Editors' Picks".

He started playing piano when he was seven years old, focusing on the classical repertoire.
As a teenager, he occasionally played piano with Batiste, including performances at Snug Harbor in the French Quarter.
Their collaboration features improvisation on several forms of western music from the 14th century to the present.
The album is named after the Roman god Janus, a two-faced god representing the album's view into music's past and future.
